[[File:Gendun Chophel.gif|thumb|A portrait of Gendun Chophel in India 1936]] '''Gendün Chöphel''' ({{Bo|t=དགེ་འདུན་ཆོས་འཕེལ།|w=dge 'dun chos 'phel}})<ref>[http://www.historychina.net/manager/info/inner.jsp?sid=1&cid=34&infoid=25285 西藏革命党考实]</ref>{{Request quotation|date=December 2017}} (1903–1951) was a Tibetan scholar, thinker, writer, and artist. He was born in 1903 in Shompongshe, Rebkong, Amdo. He was a creative and controversial figure and he is considered by many to have been one of the most important Tibetan intellectuals of the twentieth century.
Gendün Chöphel was a friend of [[Rahul Sankrityayan]]. His life was the inspiration for Luc Schaedler's film ''The Angry Monk: Reflections on Tibet''.<ref>[http://www.angrymonk.ch/ The Angry Monk: Reflections on Tibet]</ref> He is best known for his collection of essays called ''The Madman's Middle Way: Reflections on Reality of the Tibetan Monk Gendun Chophel''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lopez Jr.|first=Donald S.|title=The Madman's Middle Way: Reflections on Reality of the Tibetan Monk Gendun Choephel|year=2006|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=0-226-49316-4}}</ref> and ''Grains of Gold: Tales of a Cosmopolitan Pilgrimage'', written during his time in India and Sri Lanka in between 1934 and 1946. These essays were critical of modern [[Hinduism]], [[Christianity]], and [[British Empire|British imperialism]]. While condemning places and events like the [[Black Hole of Calcutta]] and the [[Goa Inquisition]], he praised certain British colonial practices like the abolition of [[Sati (practice)|sati]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Sources of Tibetan Tradition|editor1-first=Kurtis R|editor1-last=Schaeffer|editor2-first=Matthew T|editor2-last=Kapstein|editor3-first=Gray|editor3-last=Tuttle|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2013|chapter=Tibetans Addressing Modern Political Issues|page=753}}</ref>
